        <svcproc svcproctype="replace" graphiccount="2">
            <title>service procedure</title>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>To avoid property damage, personal injury, or death, park the vehicle on a flat level surface,
                        set the parking brake, turn the engine off, and chock the wheels.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>To avoid personal injury or death use a jack stand or equivalent support under the inter axle
                        prop shaft during the removal and installation procedure.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">
                    <emph type="bold">Inspection:</emph>
                    Compare the 10 digit part number from the label on the inter axle prop shaft, currently in the
                    vehicle, with the
                    <emph type="bold">production part number</emph>
                    listed in Table 1. Note, the identification label can be viewed by peeling off the top layer that
                    protects the label from paint. If the two numbers match, then the correct inter axle prop shaft is
                    already in the vehicle. Do not perform this Service Procedure.
                </para>
                <para>If the part numbers do not match, continue to Step 2.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Raise the forward rear axle and support with jack stands. This will spread the distance
                    between the tandem axles and aid the removal of the inter axle prop shaft.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the four bearing strap mounting bolts (Figure 1) from the forward rear tandem
                    axle output yoke.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f059071" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/g059071.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="432px"
                         scalefitheight="248px"/>
                <caption>Figure 1. Remove / Install Bearing Caps</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. Bearing Strap</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. Mounting Bolts</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. Yoke</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Compress the slip joint of the inter axle prop shaft for removal clearance and
                    disconnect the inter axle shaft from the yoke.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Repeat Steps 1 and 2 for the other end of the inter axle prop shaft.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the inter axle prop shaft from the vehicle.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install the new inter axle prop shaft, using new bearing straps, following Steps 1 to 4
                    in reverse order. Make sure the bearing caps are seated correctly (Figure 2). Tighten the bearing
                    strap mounting bolts:
                </para>
            </step1>
            <seqlist>
                <item>
                    <para>1710 U-Joint Series: 115 to 135 Lbf-ft (156 to 183 Nm)</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>SPL170 U-Joint Series: 100 to 120 Lbf-ft (136 to 163 Nm)</para>
                </item>
            </seqlist>
            <figure id="f059071" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/g059072.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="352px"
                         scalefitheight="328px"/>
                <caption>Figure 2. Insure Bearing Caps are Seated in Yoke</caption>
            </figure>
        </svcproc>
